<subSubSection pageId="56" pageNumber="57" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,554,153,180]" box="[151,554,153,180]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,554,153,180]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,554,153,180]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
Family 
<taxonomicName authority="Leach, 1815" authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[247,554,153,180]" class="Insecta" family="Corduliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Corduliidae Leach, 1815</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="56.[151,1437,225,432]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
This worldwide family is represented in 
<collectingCountry box="[603,777,225,252]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
by two genera with three species. Their body colour varies from glossy green to matt black, sometimes with small yellow to brown spots. Corduliids are very fast flying, typically rather fugitive and can often be found well away from the water. Once mating tandems are formed, couples hang on small twigs, sometimes away from water. Females lay their eggs alone, directly into water. Another species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys-Longchamps" authorityYear="1871" box="[151,414,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Corduliidae" genus="Hemicordulia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oceanica">
<emphasis box="[151,414,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Hemicordulia oceanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was long considered to be native to 
<collectingCountry box="[834,1010,369,396]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
, but now it is clear that this species is restricted to the Society Islands, 
<collectingCountry box="[517,710,405,431]" name="French Polynesia" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">French Polynesia</collectingCountry>
(Lietinck 1975).
</paragraph>
